\subsection*{(a) Definition of Electric Current and Current Density}

Electric current, denoted by \( I \), is the rate at which charge flows through a surface. It is defined as:
\[
I = \frac{dQ}{dt}
\]
where \( Q \) is the charge and \( t \) is time.

Current density, denoted by \( \mathbf{J} \), is the amount of electric current flowing per unit area of a cross-section. It is given by:
\[
\mathbf{J} = \frac{I}{A}
\]
where \( A \) is the area through which the current flows.

\subsection*{(b) Quantization of Charge}

When we say that a quantity of charge is quantized, we mean that charge exists in discrete packets rather than a continuous distribution. The fundamental unit of charge is the charge of an electron, \( e \), which is approximately \( 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{C} \). Thus, any charge \( Q \) can be expressed as:
\[
Q = n \cdot e
\]
where \( n \) is an integer.

\subsection*{(c) Copper Bar Problem}

Consider a copper bar with a rectangular cross-section of width \( w = 5.6 \, \text{mm} \) and height \( h = 50 \, \mu\text{m} \). The electron density is \( n = 8.5 \times 10^{28} \, \text{m}^{-3} \). A uniform current of \( i = 2.4 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{A} \) flows through the strip.

\subsubsection*{(i) Magnitude of the Current Density}

The area \( A \) of the cross-section is:
\[
A = w \times h = (5.6 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m}) \times (50 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{m}) = 2.8 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}^2
\]

The current density \( \mathbf{J} \) is:
\[
\mathbf{J} = \frac{i}{A} = \frac{2.4 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{A}}{2.8 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}^2} = 8.57 \times 10^{2} \, \text{A/m}^2
\]

\subsubsection*{(ii) Magnitude of the Drift Speed}

The drift speed \( v_d \) is given by:
\[
v_d = \frac{i}{n \cdot e \cdot A}
\]
Substituting the known values:
\[
v_d = \frac{2.4 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{A}}{(8.5 \times 10^{28} \, \text{m}^{-3}) \times (1.602 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{C}) \times 2.8 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}^2}
\]
\[
v_d \approx 6.34 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m/s}
\]

\subsubsection*{(iii) Explanation of High Current with Small Drift Speed}

The current is relatively high despite the small drift speed because of the high electron density in the copper. The large number of charge carriers per unit volume compensates for the slow movement of individual electrons, resulting in a substantial total current.

