\section*{Problem}

An oscillating voltage of high frequency is applied to a load by means of a copper wire of radius \SI{1}{\milli\meter}. Given that the skin depth is \( \delta = 6.6 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m} \) for this frequency, what is the high-frequency resistance per unit length of the wire in terms of its direct current resistance per unit length? [University of Durham 1966]

\section*{Solution}

The resistance per unit length of a wire at high frequency, \( R_{\text{hf}} \), is related to the direct current resistance per unit length, \( R_{\text{dc}} \), by the skin effect. The skin effect causes the current to be concentrated near the surface of the conductor, effectively reducing the cross-sectional area through which the current flows.

The direct current resistance per unit length is given by:
\[
R_{\text{dc}} = \frac{1}{\pi a^2 \sigma}
\]
where \( a = \SI{1}{\milli\meter} = \SI{1e-3}{\meter} \) is the radius of the wire and \( \sigma \) is the conductivity of copper.

At high frequencies, the effective cross-sectional area is reduced to the annular region of thickness equal to the skin depth \( \delta \). The high-frequency resistance per unit length is then:
\[
R_{\text{hf}} = \frac{1}{2\pi a \delta \sigma}
\]

The ratio of the high-frequency resistance to the direct current resistance is:
\[
\frac{R_{\text{hf}}}{R_{\text{dc}}} = \frac{\pi a^2 \sigma}{2\pi a \delta \sigma} = \frac{a}{2\delta}
\]

Substituting the given values:
\[
\frac{R_{\text{hf}}}{R_{\text{dc}}} = \frac{\SI{1e-3}{\meter}}{2 \times 6.6 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{m}} = \frac{1}{2 \times 6.6 \times 10^{-2}} = \frac{1}{0.132} \approx 7.58
\]

Thus, the high-frequency resistance per unit length is approximately 7.58 times the direct current resistance per unit length.

