\section*{Derivation of \(\mathbf{B} = \mu_0(\mathbf{H} + \mathbf{M})\)}

The magnetic flux density \(\mathbf{B}\) is related to the magnetic field strength \(\mathbf{H}\) and the magnetization \(\mathbf{M}\) of the material by the equation:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B} = \mu_0 (\mathbf{H} + \mathbf{M})
\end{equation}

where \(\mu_0\) is the permeability of free space. This equation indicates that the magnetic flux density \(\mathbf{B}\) is the sum of the applied magnetic field \(\mathbf{H}\) and the magnetization \(\mathbf{M}\), scaled by the permeability of free space.

\section*{Dependence of \(\mathbf{B}\) on Material Type}

The dependence of \(\mathbf{B}\) on the material type can be briefly described as follows:

\subsection*{(a) Paramagnetics}

In paramagnetic materials, the magnetization \(\mathbf{M}\) is directly proportional to the applied magnetic field \(\mathbf{H}\), but the proportionality constant is small. Therefore, the equation becomes:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B} = \mu_0 \left( \mathbf{H} + \chi_m \mathbf{H} \right) = \mu_0 (1 + \chi_m) \mathbf{H}
\end{equation}

where \(\chi_m\) is the magnetic susceptibility of the paramagnetic material. Since \(\chi_m\) is positive but small, \(\mathbf{B}\) is slightly greater than \(\mu_0 \mathbf{H}\).

\subsection*{(b) Ferromagnetics}

In ferromagnetic materials, the magnetization \(\mathbf{M}\) is much larger and can be non-linear with respect to \(\mathbf{H}\). The relationship is complex and often involves hysteresis. However, the general form remains:

\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{B} = \mu_0 (\mathbf{H} + \mathbf{M})
\end{equation}

In this case, \(\mathbf{B}\) can be significantly larger than \(\mu_0 \mathbf{H}\) due to the large \(\mathbf{M}\).

